reviews.review_text: Berkeley Heads, Unite! I was surprised to not find any reviews on this one yet.  I know the Roadtrip Series (vol. 1 no. 3) covers a good chunk of the '71 summer, but this show should not be overlooked as a quality performance.  I really enjoyed Brokedown Palace and Me and Bobby Mcgee.  The second half of Not Fade Away goes crazy! and track #24 is really a shout out to David Crosby who was celebrating his 30th birthday.  Jerry crunches out happy birthday on the geetar.  Berkeley Community Theater is something that I have personally only experienced with visiting the Wavy Gravy birthday, Seva benefit celebrations in the 2000's (cut me some slack - I'm from Kansas) but I loved the theater so much that it prompted me to search it out in the Grateful Dead history here on the Internet Archive.  This is a fun addition to any collection.

What What the hell is that horrible shrill noise in Cumberland?  The right channel sounds like its ripping my speaker apart. Beware. DAng. It's wonderful up until that point.  Issues in Cumberland.  Haven't gotten past that yet.

Phil it up!!! Phil's sound was damn fine on this night.  Just crisp, clear tones coming in warm waves from his bass.  C. Charlie & El Paso are prime examples of his craft.  The 1st set is the difference maker for this show.

shame about Cumberland Although it is a shame about Cumberland (and PITB), I was about to give this show five stars because it is truly one of my favorite Dead eras - the time I became a Dead Head. But that would leave no higher rating for the Anthem & AoxomoxoA (Live/Dead) shows of '68, '69 & 1970. And those were the ultimate Grateful Dead shows.

Space? Trip? I'm going to guess that Mr. Bates is an 80's and 90's Dead Head (I'm 60's and early 70's).

What is the purpose of track # 17 "Space"? It's just part of "The Other One". Please refer to side two of Skull & Roses: There is nothing called 'Drums', 'Space', or 'Jam'. Verse one, verse two, chorus, 'space', 'jam' and yes, the drums are all part of one song called The Other One. When you dice a song up into separate tracks you destroy the continuity. Why do so few of the uploaders seem to get this?

Take a few steps back and show us the whole forest. Stop labeling every single tree!

Best Uncle John's Band? There have been a lot of great versions of Uncle John's Band but there is something about this one in particular which keeps me coming back. All around great show and great recording.

I'm so not a Dead connisewwwwer. I love all these recordings especially the one with Janis Joplin. I do like the arguments among Dead Heads about what show was best or what version of the 700000000000 versions of whatever song is the best. To the layman, such as myself, it's just like listening to heaven to hear the boys play at all. Woooooooooooooo hooooooooooooooo!!!!!!

Phil's monster bass bombs and sweet vocals I am loving Phil's new supercharged bass in this recording- only a few weeks old at this point. Phil is up front in the mix and laying down earth-thumping bombs throughout.  This is a recording for the Lesh lovers of the world. Of course, you expect Phil's bass to be a highlight in songs like Sugeree and The Other One and you won't be disappointed here.  But check out Me & My Uncle! I must confess that I have not always the biggest fan of  M&MU (especially by the 1980s), but in 1971 they did some very crunchy, tasty versions. In this version Phil drops his trademark siesmic bass bombs in unexpected ways. But it's difficult to pick out just one fave Phil passage in this recording.  What are yours?
The other great part of this recording is the boys are all in fine voice and hitting their harmonies (mostly).  No overdub vocals needed here as they did on their live albums in the early 1970s. I love the vocals in this Brokedown Palace, still a new song at the time.  So sweet.
